# Engineering principles

## Defaults

- Less is more: prefer simple over simplistic; aim for concise, modular, elegant code.
- Follow codebase and community conventions/style.
- Prefer early-exit guard clauses over nested/spaghetti control flow.
- Never fail silently — fail loud with a clear, actionable error.
- Keep logic flat and readable; avoid unnecessary inner helper functions.
- Prefer proven, lightweight, composable tools over hand-rolled scripts (e.g. logrotate
  for log rotation).
- No dead code.

## Tracer bullets — close the loop

- Build the quickest end-to-end, testable MVP that exercises the whole path start to
  finish, then iterate toward the final, planned solution.
- A thin slice working end to end beats a half-built perfect layer.

## Systems thinking

- Think about the whole. Weigh how a change interacts with the rest of the system —
  upstream/downstream effects, interfaces, and second-order consequences — not just the
  local edit.

## Naming & style

- Prefer self-documenting names over terse abbreviations (`p4_changelist` over `cl`);
  stop before restating the type/implementation in the name.
- Avoid Hungarian notation.
- `snake_case` > `camelCase`.
- Spaces > tabs.

## When no clear convention applies, prefer

- YAGNI.
- SOLID — especially the Single Responsibility Principle.
- Separation of Concerns.
- Unix philosophy.
- The Pragmatic Programmer — tracer bullets (above) and fixing broken windows.
- Functional programming — the pragmatism of OCaml/F#.
- The Zen of Python — explicit, simple, flat, readable, practical, loud on errors.
